    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Guns, Arcades and the N.R.A.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Sven Moller says May 24 Topics of The Times editorial which opposes NRA plan to set up theme restaurant and arcade in Times Square objects to free speech for NRA but does not condemn anti-gun forces for advocating elimination of Second Amendment</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The N.R.A. in Times Square'' (Topics of The Times, May 24) objects to the National Rifle Association's setting up a theme restaurant and arcade in midtown Manhattan. As a liberal and a gun owner, I find it disturbing that you object to free speech for the N.R.A. but do not condemn anti-gun forces for advocating the elimination of the Second Amendment.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''The N.R.A. in Times Square'' (Topics of The Times, May 24) objects to the National Rifle Association's setting up a theme restaurant and arcade in midtown Manhattan. As a liberal and a gun owner, I find it disturbing that you object to free speech for the N.R.A. but do not condemn anti-gun forces for advocating the elimination of the Second Amendment.</p>
        <p>The N.R.A. is the only effective organization that fights for gun owners' rights to defend themselves. The organization draws many members, who may or may not agree with all its policies. It represents many middle-class Americans who enjoy shooting or hunting. If the Times Square establishment draws an audience, it should stay open. If it doesn't, it will close for economic reasons. Let the market decide.</p>
        <p>SVEN  MOLLER  South Salem, N.Y., May 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
